REASON FOR USCAROT: CAROTID OBSTRUCTION PT BRINGING PRIOR FILMS\.br\

Impression: #1Jefferson class C (16-49% diameter reduction) of the right and left internal carotid artery. The right internal coronary artery is at the high end at approximately 49%. #2 Bilateral cranial vertebral arterial flow.

\.br\\.br\ Carotid artery Doppler ultrasound performed 7 February 2002.\.br\\.br\ Clinical History: Carotid stenosis.\.br\\.br\ Technique: Utilizing a linear transducer sonographic interrogation of the carotid arteries was performed.\.br\\.br\ Findings: Evaluation of the right carotid arterial system demonstrates a peak systolic velocity of the mid common carotid artery of 85 cm/sec. The peak systolic velocity of the distal internal carotid artery was 79 cm/sec. This constitutes an ICA/CCA ratio of 1. There is diffuse mild to moderate atheromatous hard plaque at the carotid bifurcation extending into the internal and external carotid artery. No significant carotid artery stenosis is demonstrated. The peak systolic velocity in the external carotid artery was 117 cm/sec. The area under systole within the internal carotid artery demonstrates diffuse spectral broadening.\.br\\.br\ Evaluation of the left carotid arterial system demonstrates a peak systolic velocity of the proximal common carotid arteries of 94 cm/sec. Peak systolic velocity the mid internal carotid artery was 102 cm/sec. This constitutes an ICA/CCA ratio of approximately 1.1. There is diffuse hard calcified atheromatous plaque at the bifurcation extending into both the internal and external carotid artery. There is diffuse spectral broadening within the proximal internal carotid artery under systole.\.br\\.br\ The peak systolic velocity in the external carotid artery was 115 cm/sec. There is bilateral cranial vertebral arterial flow.\.br\\.br\
